comments.body:
Maybe something like:
```diff
diff --git a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/BuildLibCalls.cpp b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/BuildLibCalls.cpp
index 97f11ca71726..7a2938ba26d6 100644
--- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/BuildLibCalls.cpp
+++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/BuildLibCalls.cpp
@@ -1231,6 +1231,23 @@ static Value *emitLibCall(LibFunc TheLibFunc, Type *ReturnType,
   FunctionCallee Callee = M->getOrInsertFunction(FuncName, FuncType);
   inferLibFuncAttributes(M, FuncName, *TLI);
   CallInst *CI = B.CreateCall(Callee, Operands, FuncName);
+
+  // If the Operand is an Argument, use its ArgNo to find its ParamAttrs. Copy
+  // them to the new CallInst's ParamAttrs.
+  unsigned NewArgNo = 0;
+  for (Value *Operand : Operands) {
+    if (auto *A = dyn_cast<Argument>(Operand)) {
+      Function *F = A->getParent();
+      AttributeList AL = F->getAttributes();
+      unsigned ArgNo = A->getArgNo();
+      AttributeSet ParamAttrs = AL.getParamAttrs(ArgNo);
+
+      for (const Attribute &A : ParamAttrs)
+        CI->addParamAttr(NewArgNo, A);
+    }
+    ++NewArgNo;
+  }
+
   if (const Function *F =
           dyn_cast<Function>(Callee.getCallee()->stripPointerCasts()))
     CI->setCallingConv(F->getCallingConv());
```

To give a specific testcase, consider the following:

```
#include <string.h>
char* f (const char z) {
    return strchr("foobar", z);
}
```

The strchr gets converted to memchr.  With `-mregparm=3`, all three arguments to the memchr need to be marked inreg.  Where does the "7" get its inreg marking?   The only way we know it needs an inreg marking is by querying NumRegisterParameters.

The "libcall" handling in SelectionDAG only gets called for libcalls that are generated by SelectionDAG (e.g. from lowering intrinsics like llvm.memcpy).  If we're generating libcalls at the IR level, I think we need an equivalent codepath that works on IR.  Or some sort of marking to let the backend know the inreg attributes are missing.
